If you made it to the end thanks for reading my random kvetching haha and hey, if there is a series like those by an mlm/trans author specifically about a trans mlm experience, please prove me wrong because I want to read it LOL

And in many ways, why I write is to try desperately to fill that void, because I know somebody is waiting to read gay/trans SFF that is in the same milieu as your Broken Earth trilogies and your Jade Wars or your Locked Tomb series or (insert massive recent SFF series here)

I'm not talking about YA here, not that it's worth less, but that when you're in Adult SFF, you find readers of Adult SFF. I see the YA coming out in the veins of "Cemetery Boys" etc, and as much as that is good, I'm looking for Adult SFF.

the ONLY book/series off the top of my head that even comes close to the likes of A Memory Called Empire/Gideon the Ninth/Black Sun/Priory of the Orange Tree and so on is "Ninefox Gambit" by Yoon Ha Lee.

Idk I definitely think there ought to be room for all of us, it's not abt sapphic characters in books being overrepresented or some bullshit, but the lack of focus on works of the same calibre featuring an mlm experience (and don't get me started on books centering trans people)

I've said it before, I'll say it again: Loving the waves of sapphic SFF books that have won Hugos/Nebulas, been blockbuster titles, evolved into genre staples, etc. The fact that I'm struggling to think of SFF featuring and written by mlm authors (with the same quality) is... 🥺

Your story, though it may share certain archetypes or elements or themes, still matters because it's your own. Repetition and re-vitilization are the backbone of literary tradition, not its pitfalls !

Certain tropes exist, especially in SFF, they're gonna cross over and osmose into your writing whether or not you sat down nefariously ready to 'steal' another book's lore or whatever. That's what happens when you read and absorb information, it becomes part of you too.

Every day I have to re-convince myself that finding similarities to my characters or books in the work of other authors doesn't mean I subliminally plagiarized them, it just means that all works are connected intertextually and that's just part of creating fiction!!

Lol anyway it’s gotten to the point where I’m just rambling but ig I just want it to be known—other ppl in the Puerto Rican diaspora, I really am trying to write something for us this time

But at the same time, I want to get across the beautiful things about having this identity, bc I am proud of it. I love the sense of community between Nuyoricans and the way even smaller things like food and music remind us of each other

Today I looked up information about Puerto Ricans in legal careers, and what I got was scholarly papers about “why Puerto Ricans are the most critically underserved legal demographic.” 1% of lawyers in the US are Puerto Rican. In NY, there are 2 PR lawyers for every 1 Million ppl

There’s this sense of guilt, of never feeling like enough in a world that was specifically built to crush you. (Speaking for myself) Even your successes can’t really be worth it. You always have to be something bigger, smarter, the best, but there’s no support network for that

This isn’t rlly something I’ve ever seen explored in fiction, and rarely if ever. Certainly not in SFF. There are all these nuances to Nuyorican identity, esp as an LGBT person; I want to create something intelligible here that other children of diaspora will just Know

With KoAB I think I’m hitting on aspects of Emil’s character that I haven’t necessarily been fully exploring in other “versions” of him. It’s a fantasy world, but I rlly do intend him to be Puerto Rican coded (specifically Nuyorican)

(Drew POV) Two rubbed the back of his neck—equally disturbing to watch him act out all my mannerisms. “Or at least accept that I’m here. Or defeat me? But I’m not trying to hurt you. You’d only be hurting yourself.”

(Drew POV) I could ignore a lot of shit, but I was hitting the end of my tether. I couldn’t escape this feeling—this desire that snuck up to pull an ugly prank on me. I hadn’t recognized it, and I had no idea what to do, but I wanted Ertan so badly it almost made me nauseous.

(Ertan POV) I was calm, though something pathetic in my psyche was thrashing and miserable—distraught at the idea of Drew coming to harm. But my fear over him meant nothing now, I was supposed to be here for him, not the other way around.

(Ertan POV) Inside the shop, the lukewarm current of AC felt miraculous. I stood very still with my arms out in front of a fan, making a huge nuisance of myself. When I recovered, I saw that Drew had already grabbed a clear plastic bag and was darting up and down the aisles.

(Drew POV) “And they can get at us too,” Ertan added. “They can touch us, talk to us—” He froze as the waitress returned for our orders, melting easily into nonchalance, but it wasn’t so easy for me. What if she heard what we were talking about?

(Drew POV)  A waitress led us over to a table and thoughtlessly put both kids and adult menus on it before departing.
“Just didn’t know what to make of me I guess,” I said in a self-deprecating way, reaching for the packet of crayons anyway.

(Ertan POV) Then he slipped my embrace and took off running as fast as his legs could carry him. Shit—what else could I do? I ran after, hardly noticing when my boots splashed through puddles. I almost felt loathe to overtake him, because then he would no longer be in my sight.

(Ertan POV) How could anybody hear the things Drew said, spend any time with him at all, and think of him as dead weight?
I wanted to pull him close and hug him, just to hold him. Just to impart any piece of the huge, choking feeling taking host in me.

(Drew POV) “I promise.” With another smile, Ertan pulled my hand to his mouth, kissing the back of it. I felt like a cartoon animal that just got hit on the head with an anvil, little planets and stars spinning around in my vision.

(Drew POV) If I was a little less of a coward, I would’ve turned around and held him. “Ertan, I’m not going to lie, the metaphysics you’re on are eluding me. I’m happy we’re here too. That it’s you, that we’re here. That we’ll have always been here.”

(Ertan POV) I could still remember with vivid detail how my parents held Fadime and Mathilda on the teacup ride, holding my Mam’s hand on the pirate ship. I would never have that again. I didn’t need it, but I could never go back…

(Ertan POV) I trailed off instead, just looking at him. He was wearing loose athletic shorts that day, which showed a lot of leg—I suddenly felt like a time traveller from the 1890’s who hadn’t seen a bare thigh before.

(Drew POV) “I don’t have a bathing suit,” I protested weakly, but getting in the water was becoming increasingly appealing.
Ertan smirked in the way he does when he’s about to cause trouble. “I don’t either."

(Drew POV) My reflection shook himself, pressing a hand against the mirror’s pane. I stepped back, my heart racing, and watched as the other Drew emerged. Everything about him was muted, from his flat expression to the grey of his body and clothing, which only grew more faded.

(Ertan POV) What few people meandered through the store, nodding along to country muzak, didn’t seem to notice the swaying lanterns that jutted up through the tile floor. Nor did they see the skeletal arms holding them.

(Ertan POV) “Wait!” I pulled out the crayons. “Like Ariadne’s string—you’ve got to make us a path out!”
Drew accepted a blue crayon, and it flickered to life in his hand. Wherever he brought it through the air, it left phantom marks like a noble gas.

(Drew POV) All through New Jersey, around snaking highway clovers, I switched out tapes as fast as I could find a song we both knew. We burned through a Weezer album, a few Johnny Cash tracks, and predictably, Queen’s Bohemian Rhapsody. I mean, were we bisexual or weren’t we?

(Drew POV) Ertan’s hand on my back felt like the only thing in the world. “You’re not dead yet, though. Espinoza said that life is just preparing for death, and we all… we all get the same chance to do so. You’re breathing right now, every moment is a miracle.”

[Drew POV] There was already some guy with his easel set up in the middle of the hall, and his shading would have made mine walk the plank. Shy and adrift without Ertan there, I shuffled between statues, making a vague effort at sketching some.

[Drew POV] Ertan, who apparently couldn’t pull his humor out of the fourth grade, kept on taking pictures of exposed butts and dicks wherever he saw them, occasionally giving a thumb’s up in the picture with them. I knew he was getting some of me too, whether I liked it or not.

[Ertan POV] I felt vile for getting jealous. I wasn’t wholly an outsider here, they welcomed me in, but the truth was that Drew had somewhere to return to, and I didn't.
In the end, I did what I do best--I put my feelings in a plastic bag, and sunk them with stones.

[Ertan POV]  I could have sworn that some of the marble statues were creeping off their plinths to follow me; I kept seeing movement in the corner of my eye, but I never caught anything, and it was deathly silent besides.

[Drew POV] “If we can make it three blocks on our lonesome,” Ertan teased. Then he reached out and easily took my hand. “Look, you’re my buddy, like on a field trip. I won’t lose you, you won’t lose me.”
[Ertan POV] But when Drew spoke my name, it felt like an invocation, as if calling me into being. Conjuring me up.

[Drew POV] I didn’t mind Anais’ morbid fascination, except when it reminded me that I was basically a thread away from perishing at any time. Literally any given moment.
I tightened my hands on the wheel. Maybe Ertan should have kept driving.

[Drew POV] Watching Ertan drive yesterday was getting under my skin. I couldn’t get my eyes off his hands, the way his wrists stuck out when he turned the wheel. After a while it made me feel weirdly dirty to keep tearing myself away from the driver’s side...

[Ertan POV] Before we went to check out, I made sure both my special rocks and my nine hot sauce bottles were stowed away in my satchel. Drew caught me doing it, laughing. “I forgot, you’re like a fucking magpie. Got enough treasures, almighty Smaug?”

[Drew POV] We went past the shark tank and the moray eels, each tank revealing a strange and disparate world. My hands itched for a pencil, longing to sketch them. I was just like those sharks—they couldn’t stop swimming or they’d die, and I couldn’t stop making art either.

[Drew POV] Ertan never let his strife go with an open hand. He always held onto it until the last possible moment. Anger surged in me for an instant, rage at his dad for making him feel like this, but I had to choke it down.

[Ertan POV] We made our snack pit stop, grabbing cookie dough ice cream to share. “Doesn’t that make you sick?” I asked, when I noticed Drew clutching the carton of Breyer’s.
He made one of his little faces. “You only live once, man. What am I gonna do?”

[Ertan POV] Drew put a hand to his mouth to stifle some wheezing, stepped-on dog toy laughter. “That’s so bad, I shouldn’t be laughing… that’s not fucking funny.”
“Au contraire, I think it’s hilarious. And don’t the bleakest things make the funniest stories?”

[Drew POV] The car was hideous. The paint was mostly this odd champagne color, but for some reason the back doors were both dark brown. Huge spots of rust crawled up from under the wheels. The tracings of unsuccessfully removed bumper stickers clung to the chassis.
[Ertan POV] Like a Lovecraft protagonist driven mad by looking down some big hole in the ocean, I’d spent the past few days lingering around in a stupor and refusing to accept my reality.

[Drew POV] I also vividly remembered the day, only a week after moving in, I’d sat on my bed with the family laptop and nervously started Googling things like “what is a trans person?” and “how do you become trans?” in the Incognito browser.

15) Electress Melwr IV of the Escarpau- the head of the current ruling family on the isle of Saerum. She is militaristic and steadfast, but surprises diplomats by seeming down to earth and comradely.

14) The Fisherman-a well-known smuggler and peddler who travels the Kiir coastline, generally along the same routes as the Seaside Players. He and Darius are friends, and he passes information to the Troupe

13) Marcelle Trask-the last Troupe member. A strong and capable woman who once ran a mercantile house. She often attempts to 'mom friend' the other Troupe members, but she's just as bad as them. She prefers to play knights and roles with combat potential.

12) Ettiene Haulfman-another Troupe member, a map-maker and stage manager for performances. He is around Darius' age, and carries himself with a restrained, erudite air. Onstage, he typically gravitates toward very sad roles.

11) Avery Kieran-another Troupe member. Like Valentin, half-Saerumite. He's a skilled hunter and trapper, and primarily takes care of the horses. A bit smug and self-satisfied, which leads to minor ego clashes among the Troupe. He mostly plays leading male roles.
10) Yiris Olewski-another Troupe member, the head costumer and keeper of supplies. She's stern when it comes to rations and already-thin money, but otherwise she is flamboyant and quite excessive.
9) Livvia Szygnus-another Troupe member, Valentin's best friend. She matches him in exuberance and charisma, and in holding grudges. She often plays royalty or queens, and is musically talented
8) Jules Iylas-another Troupe member, Nikita's sometime lover. He is gentle but blunt, and extremely honest. He tends to play spirits or ghosts, and is adept at changing his voice
7) Darius Gdaltr-the Troupe's director and headman, an older fellow who, like Elis, is descended from the Tzaiteran Protectorate. He is kind and thoughtful, and does his best to look after his people

6) Lorelei St.Rhodes-the daughter of the Saerumite Merchant-Governor of Laluns (Kiir's ancient capitol). Serious and beautiful, secretly harbors traitorous intent against her family. Her father would like to marry her off, but she has her eye on the ruthless Widakov

5) The Highwayman, Arkady Widakov-an enigmatic man with no past who wanders Kiir, at turns slaughtering Saerumite and Vircinean nobles and profiteering off their war against each other. His only goal is survival. That is, until he meets Lorelei St.Rhodes
4) Nikita Borisych-another Seaside Player, a convict from a Vircinean prison colony who has been on the run for 15 years. He is witty and sharp, somewhat mischevious, and often plays villains.

3) Roman Solevsky-a deserter from the Vircinean conscript army, who recently escaped imprisonment and joined the Troupe. He is often quiet, but analytical and philosophical, although he is surprisingly talented at acting, and no one would be suspicious of his hiding place

2) Valentin Revin-the principle actor of a theatre troupe in occupied Kiir. He is extremely charismatic and personable, and mostly plays female parts. He sees the Troupe as a method of insurgency against the two occupying forces, and is passionate about standing up to them

1) The Scribe, Elis Khlrot-an acolyte of the All-Seeing Mother of Gods, Omniya, she functions as a journalist and also the narrator of the story. She's serious but clever and devoted to her faith. She is also extremely knowledgeable on world cultures and languages!

I want people to be able read this fucked up chimera of Shakespeare references and Noir and Gaslamp elements and alien beasts and extraordinarily gay characters and anti-capitalist sentiment and Pithy Details about Floating City Mechanics! I care about it very much (11/12)

That no editors or agents are allowed even for a SECOND to assume these characters are white, cis, het or non-neurodiverse. I am still trying. I think this book is meaningful, especially as a gestalt worth more than the hackneyed sum of its "A Plot" and assorted details (10/12)

This is a book I basically had to write my own Wiki for Before Even Starting To Write, so I could get down all the relevant world-building that was essential to plot--and even then, I kept adding things! And I'll be forced to glaze over it, just to make sure... (9/12)

Hell, it makes ME want to give up, for all the above reasons and then some. Partly because it's like, okay, if I can't "market" this then why did I write it, it's fucking useless and a waste of time and nobody will ever want to acquire it. Sending it out would be futile (8/12)

To distill a 130k word story that Needed To Be That Long for a Reason into one single-spaced page is probably a reason why a lot of neurodivergent authors just give up. It's an unfriendly process with a million online guides each giving their 2 bits on how to do it right (7/12)

ESPEcially in Adult SFF. My original bullet-pointed, no complete sentences outline for this book was 16 pages long. I also have ADHD--I write like how I talk. I do not talk in choppy, stilted, short paragraphs. Expecting some1 whose brain goes 1000 miles a minute... (6/12)

Even taking time to mention ONE of these things would burn word-count that I don't have. A book can't be a single plot. We're focusing on writing things that are 'marketable' and 'condensable' and make nice pithy blurbs instead of things that intrinsically matter. (5/12)

The same is true for race and ethnicity. Maybe it doesn't matter for "plot" if my characters are all mixed, but it matters! That's who they are! And if I don't say it, again, the mostly white editors and agents I send to will assume the default--whiteness (4/12)

This wouldn't be the same story if Jack was cis, there are Thematic Elements there and also nobody needs a reason to be cis or trans--but at the same time, I'm stuck, because without bringing it up that leaves room for agents to assume the default--that he IS cis (3/12)

All four of my MCs are gay. One of them is transmasc and another is a nonbinary lesbian. The typical "just put your A Plot" into the synopsis format leaves me nowhere to put this information. It's not essential to the "plot" but it IS essential to the book (2/12)

9. Terez Marshall, one of my MCs, was originally supposed to be able to mind control people. This made them way too powerful, so now they are just strong and able to communicate with the weird animals on the planet's surface

8. In this world, all currency is based on silicon, and its backed by tiny microscopic creatures called diatoms! Diatoms can metabolize silicon, they incorporate it into their bodies, so the total health of the diatom colonies=the value of the currency
7. The first character I came up with was Jack Gany, and his name is kind of a weird pun based off the play As You Like It...

6. Before I started writing aNYTHING I spent like six weeks making a long-ass lore document where I wrote down basically every piece of worldbuilding I could think of off the top of my head, and justifications for all the arguments that could possibly be made against things :|

4. Lot of laws and religious theory in Cambria is based on Shakespeare! A handwritten omnibus of plays was the only real book that survived to them from earth, and seemed like some religious text, so jurisprudence is predicated on these themes.

3. Cambria, the ship-city where the story is set, is a huge melange from a lot of influences! Including 'Devil in the White City,' the traction towns from 'Mortal Engines,' Santaphrax in 'The Edge Chronicles,' + New York, Boston and Chicago.
2. I've given the two main ships my own dorky little ship names (Reversed Judgment for Jack and Cassim, Starcrossed for Terez and Fernanda)

Sometimes I actually like reading sff set in worlds with homo/transphobia, because the characters' actions genuinely ring truer to things I feel every day, and not to escapismland, which again... is just fine, but not as meaningful to me on this level.

situations that I, in the real world, am frustrated with. Scenarios where being gay isn't just alright, Because I experience those worries in real life, not in spite of that. I think it's important to see your own struggle, as important as it is to see those like you thrive.

I wanted to write about a strange new world with fascinating problems where the characters are all gay or trans and they struggle over it. The real world is full of frustration and pain, and to me identity doesn't need to have pain in it, but it can. I still wanted to show...

But I don't agree with this argument that all scifi has to be this way. I've written books where it's all normalized, not an issue at all, yet for my current WIP I'm writing in a sci-fi world where it intentionally isn't just okay to be gay. I'm gay, I made that call. Why?

or transphobia. If you can control everything, you MUST remove these forces from your world. And in a sense, I get it, I respect authors who do this, and I like reading books where space war or whatever is happening, but it's not a big problem that the main character is gay...

The discussion around making "LGBT-normative" sci fi worlds is very interesting because I've only ever seen one side of it: that if you're creating a world, then you are allowed to pick and choose what everything is like, and it's therefore morally wrong to include homophobia...

I’m a crab down in the bucket. Where are my fellow crabs? Everybody else who can’t write palatable Cis People literature or marketable stories or smile with full white teeth on a book flap. I don’t want to have to pinch the other crabs, I wish we could all crawl out together!

Which is why even tho I liked That Book which was supposed to speak to my,, gaytrans latine Experience what I felt was a lot of “latinidad” broad stroking and a lot of “explaining transness for cis readers” and it was like I was reading a book not actually meant for me

Maybe this is too far but some of us gaytrans aoc are like the underground man from notes from the underground. I’m never going to come up from under the floorboards ! You won’t catch me making myself palatable for anybody. I’m not interested in assimilation or normativity

I’m going to keep writing my embarrassing gritty little books with characters who aren’t supposed to be a “window” for anybody. They just are. I’ll never be marketable as an author because I’ll probably never “pass” and I’ve made my peace w it on a personal level

And like big ups to that person I guess for figuring it out and getting Deals . But we’re still in the bucket, I’m still pinching these other crabs with everything I have and it’s clear only those of us who can act normative will get money in the end

I said this months ago but I have such a feeling now that publishing seems to have found one author of my particular marginalizations to throw money at, the rest of us crabs in the bucket are done for
